{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17513635","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17513635"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:12:04+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:12:04+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12169"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12169","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12169"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.62,0.22,0.1,0.04,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4697"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78143"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4697","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4697"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12169"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63565"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"2560"},{"type":"tags","id":"2778"},{"type":"tags","id":"4626"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7281"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7286"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26773"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78143","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78143"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 52-year-old woman is brought to the emergency department because of right leg weakness. In the morning, she tried to stand up and found she could not support her body and fell on the floor. Her medical history is notable for hypertension and smoking one pack per day for 30 years. The patient is right handed. On examination, her blood pressure is 181/96 mmHg, pulse 88/min. regular, temperature 37.2\u003Csup\u003Eo\u003C/sup\u003EC and respiratory rate 16/min. The patient\u2019s language is fluent, but she is unaware of any weakness. Motor power is 5/5 throughout, except for 1/5 strength in the right leg, both proximally and distally, and 4/5 strength in the proximal right arm. Decreased response to pinprick is noted on the right side. Plantar reflex shows right toe dorsiflexion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe diagram shows the cerebral vasculature (\u003Ca href=\u0022https://emedici.com/storage/images/1141c07a-bd97-4a6f-9c01-89b16270a415.jpg\u0022\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EImage\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/a\u003E).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Occlusion of which one of the following arteries would lead to this presentation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["A","B","C","D","E"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe patient presentation with profound weakness of the right leg, with mild weakness of the right arm, and Babinski\u2019s sign would suggest cerebrovascular stroke due to occlusion of the anterior cerebral artery (\u003Cstrong\u003Eartery labelled A\u003C/strong\u003E).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOcclusion of the \u003Cstrong\u003Eartery labelled B \u003C/strong\u003E(middle cerebral artery) expected to cause motor and sensory deficits involving the face and arm, and to a lesser extent, the leg and global aphasia if occlusion occurs in the dominant hemisphere.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOcclusion of the \u003Cstrong\u003Eartery labelled C \u003C/strong\u003E(posterior cerebral artery) typically cause visual symptoms such as homonymous hemianopia or quadrantanopia and sensory deficits but seldom paralysis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOcclusion of the \u003Cstrong\u003Eartery labelled D\u003C/strong\u003E (anterior inferior cerebellar artery) would result in ipsilateral deafness, limb ataxia and facial motor/sensory loss with contralateral decreased pain/temperature.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOcclusion of the \u003Cstrong\u003Eartery labelled E \u003C/strong\u003E(posterior inferior cerebellar artery) would result in ipsilateral palatal weakness, limb ataxia and Horner syndrome with contralateral decreased pain/temperature.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Occlusion of the anterior cerebral artery will classically cause contralateral motor and sensory deficits, more prominent in the leg than the arm.","The face and tongue are usually spared. Lack of concern and disinhibition are frequently present. Incontinence may be present, as well as primitive frontal lobe reflexes (grasp and suck)."],"references":["Pare JR, Kahn JH. Basic neuroanatomy and stroke syndromes. Emerg Med Clin North Am. 2012 Aug;30(3):601-15. doi: 10.1016/j.emc.2012.05.004. PMID: 22974640. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/22974640/","Kumral E, Bayulkem G, Evyapan D, Yunten N. Spectrum of anterior cerebral artery territory infarction: clinical and MRI findings. Eur J Neurol. 2002 Nov;9(6):615-24. doi: 10.1046/j.1468-1331.2002.00452.x. PMID: 12453077. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/12453077/","Matos Casano HA, Tadi P, Ciofoaia GA. Anterior Cerebral Artery Stroke. 2023 Aug 14. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2025 Jan\u2013. PMID: 30726018. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/30726018/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63565"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12169"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"18449"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"18449","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/18449"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/1141c07a-bd97-4a6f-9c01-89b16270a415.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/1141c07a-bd97-4a6f-9c01-89b16270a415.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":1302,"height":1424}},{"type":"it